<TITLE> Stocks close down led by banks </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 21 (bdnews24.com)Stocks closed downbeat Monday led by banks, while turnover on the DSE fell from Thursday's high despite continued investor interest in state-owned Jamuna and Meghna. Market analysts say decreased interest in bank shares is due to retail investors reshaping their portfolios, with banks now relegated to the back end of trading. "A recent disclosure from the central bank, which revealed they are investigating the declared net operating profit of banks for the year, has resulted in investors taking a back foot on banking shares," said Yaweer Sayeed, CEO of AIMS of Bangladesh. The market opened with a sharp rise in the general index prior to it slumping in the midday session. Trading remained steady in the afternoon session before closing downbeat. The benchmark DGEN or general index declined 3.19 points, or 0.10 percent, to end at 2948.71. The DSI or all share price index closed at 2483.52, down 6.70 points, or 0.26 percent. The blue chip DSE-20 slumped 48.44 points, or 1.99 percent, to end on 2379.91. Turnover on the country's prime bourse fell to Tk 1.65 billion from Thursday's Tk 3.11 billion, wit5h 8,621,572 shares traded. Losers outnumbered gainers 159 to 56 with some ten issues remaining unchanged. Issues in state run oil companies, mutual funds, power and pharmaceuticals dominated Monday's trading. Meghna Petroleum topped the turnover board, closing 19.67 percent higher, at Tk 410. Jamuna Oil followed, to end at Tk 414.30, up 9.16 percent. Islami Bank continued its decline from Thursday, closing 7.49 down, to end on Tk 6281.25. The bank revealed that it has dropped its proposal to change the face value denomination of its shares. Grameen Mutual Fund One continued its rise, gaining 0.87 percent, to end on Tk 92.60. AB Bank eroded Thursday's losses, gaining 0.24 percent, to finish at Tk 2805. Among other issues on the turnover board, IFIC, Trust Bank, Square Pharma and BRAC Bank declined. State owned power company DESCO advanced. Bengal Biscuits, Jamuna Oil, Meghna Petroleum, DESCO and Mithun Knitwear were among the top gainers. ICB, Pharmaco International, M Hossain Garments, Islami Bank and Legacy Footwear topped the losers. All the indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange also ended down. The CSCX or selective categories index declined 33.02 points, or 0.67 percent, to 4842.95. The CASPI or all share price index ended at 7528.47, down 52.17 points, or 0.68 percent. The blue chip CSE-30 index closed 113.62 points, or 1.65 percent lower, at 6752.74. Turnover on the port city bourse however climbed to Tk 324.364 million from Thursday's Tk 289.686 million, with 2,016,192 shares traded. Of the traded issues 29 advanced, 99 declined and four issues held steady. bdnews
